#compdef jetmidi
# ============================================================================
# jetmidi - firewall-traversing 2-way MIDI over
#            UDP between two networked hosts
#            (Node.js, no LICENSE file declared)
#
# Author : David Konsumer
# Upstream: https://github.com/konsumer/jetmidi
# npm    : jetmidi (binary: jetmidi)
#
# `jetmidi` streams MIDI messages bidirectionally
# between two hosts over UDP, with a clever
# firewall-traversal handshake that lets both
# endpoints punch through NAT without requiring
# port forwarding or relay servers. Each side:
#   1. Creates a virtual ALSA/CoreMIDI/WinMM MIDI
#      input + output port (named "JetMIDI in"
#      and "JetMIDI out") that local DAWs can
#      route to
#   2. Sends 10 "garbage" UDP datagrams to the
#      remote peer to coax NAT translation tables
#      into existence
#   3. Sends an "ACK_MAGICK" datagram that the
#      remote peer recognizes as the handshake
#      completion signal
#   4. After handshake, every local MIDI message
#      is encapsulated in a UDP datagram + sent
#      to the peer; every received UDP datagram
#      is replayed to the local virtual output
#      port (where DAWs see it as incoming MIDI)
#
# This pattern is based on the classic
# UDP-hole-punching technique used by STUN/TURN
# for VoIP and game-server matchmaking. jetmidi
# adapts it for MIDI's low-bandwidth + low-latency
# requirements.
#
# Use cases:
#   - Remote collaboration on MIDI compositions
#     (two musicians on different home networks
#     can share a MIDI session without VPN /
#     port forwarding / external relays)
#   - Educational remote teaching (instructor's
#     keyboard MIDI streams to student's DAW
#     synth in real time)
#   - Live-performance distributed MIDI control
#     (a remote musician's controller drives an
#     on-stage instrument)
#   - Network MIDI without RTP-MIDI / AppleMIDI
#     stack (jetmidi's UDP protocol is simpler +
#     more firewall-friendly than the RFC 6295
#     RTP-MIDI flow)
#
# Usage:
#   jetmidi --ip <remote-host> \
#           [--port <local-udp-port>] \
#           [--destination <remote-udp-port>] \
#           [--verbose]
#
# Flags (yargs declarative):
#   -i, --ip <host>                - destination
#                                     IP address
#                                     of the
#                                     remote peer
#                                     (required)
#   -p, --port <port>              - local UDP
#                                     port to
#                                     bind for
#                                     receiving
#                                     (default
#                                     5556)
#   -d, --destination <port>       - remote UDP
#                                     port to
#                                     send to
#                                     (default
#                                     5557)
#   -v, --verbose                  - verbose
#                                     debugging
#                                     info
#                                     (logs every
#                                     MIDI
#                                     message
#                                     sent +
#                                     received)
#   -h, --help                     - print yargs
#                                     help
#
# Symmetric-peer configuration example:
#   # On host A (LAN IP 192.168.0.5):
#   jetmidi -i 192.168.0.4
#   # On host B (LAN IP 192.168.0.4):
#   jetmidi -i 192.168.0.5 -p 5557 -d 5556
#
#   # The port/destination pair is swapped on
#   # the second peer so each side's outbound
#   # port matches the other side's inbound port.
#
# Internet-peer example (NAT traversal):
#   # Each peer needs to know the other's
#   # public IP + port. Coordination typically
#   # via Discord/Slack/email pre-session.
#   # On home network behind NAT:
#   jetmidi -i 203.0.113.42 -v
#
# The midi lane is built on `midi ^0.9.2`
# (declared verbatim at upstream package.json
# HEAD as a direct dep, imported as
# `var midi = require('midi')` in index.js line
# 10, used at lines 41-43 to create virtual MIDI
# input + output ports `new midi.input()` +
# `input.openVirtualPort('JetMIDI in')` +
# `output.sendMessage(out)` for sending received
# UDP-encapsulated messages to the local virtual
# output port), the canonical Node MIDI library
# by Justin Latimer (justinlatimer) - github.com/
# justinlatimer/node-midi.
#
# Justin Latimer's node-midi is the de-facto
# canonical Node MIDI library:
#   - Wraps the rtmidi C++ library (Gary P.
#     Scavone's cross-platform MIDI I/O
#     abstraction) via node-gyp native addon
#   - Cross-platform MIDI I/O (Linux ALSA +
#     macOS CoreMIDI + Windows WinMM/WinRT +
#     JACK)
#   - 100,000+ weekly npm downloads
#   - Stable API since 2012; minimal breaking
#     changes between major versions
#   - Virtual port support (Linux + macOS;
#     Windows requires loopMIDI or similar
#     external bridge)
#   - Input callback-based + output direct-call
#     APIs
#   - Sysex (System Exclusive) message support
#
# node-midi's distinguishing position vs
# alternatives:
#   - justinlatimer/midi (Latimer): canonical;
#     the npm `midi` package; THIS AXIS
#   - @julusian/midi (Julian Waller's
#     maintained fork): newer; better Node 18+
#     compatibility; active maintenance after
#     Latimer's original lapsed
#   - easymidi (Tom Dinchak): higher-level
#     event-based wrapper over @julusian/midi
#   - jzz (Jazz-Soft): pure-JS MIDI library
#     using Web MIDI API in browser + jzz-midi
#     bindings in Node; alternative pure-JS
#     path
#
# The Latimer/Julusian split mirrors common
# Node ecosystem patterns where a popular
# library transitions from original-author
# maintenance to community-fork maintenance.
# Both packages remain canonical in different
# contexts:
#   - `midi` (Latimer): used by older projects
#     locked to a specific version
#   - `@julusian/midi`: used by newer projects
#     that need active maintenance + Node 18+
#     support
#
# Justin Latimer's broader Node ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - node-midi (canonical Node MIDI; THIS AXIS)
#   - Various smaller utility libraries around
#     real-time audio + MIDI integration
#   - Ad-hoc contributions to the wider Node
#     audio + music-software ecosystem
#
# Latimer's role in the Node ecosystem is
# *specialized real-time audio/MIDI infrastructure*
# - similar position to Patrick Klein's role in
# Rust (midir at Axis 269 Rust slot R1505) +
# Marc Rene Arns's role in Go (gomidi at Axis
# 269 Go slot R1506).
#
# The three canonical MIDI authors form a
# cross-language *specialized-protocol-author*
# cluster, each canonical for their respective
# language ecosystem:
#   - Rust: Patrick Klein / Boddlnagg / midir
#   - Go: Marc Rene Arns / gomidi org
#   - Node: Justin Latimer / node-midi
#
# All three wrap or interface with operating
# system MIDI APIs (ALSA + CoreMIDI + WinMM/
# WinRT), with the Rust lane being the only
# pure-language implementation (the Go + Node
# lanes wrap rtmidi C++ via cgo + node-gyp
# respectively).
#
# jetmidi uses node-midi in index.js to:
#   1. Create virtual MIDI input + output ports
#      (`new midi.input()` + `input.openVirtualPort
#      ('JetMIDI in')` + `new midi.output()` +
#      `output.openVirtualPort('JetMIDI out')`)
#   2. Receive MIDI messages from the virtual
#      input port via the `input.on('message',
#      callback)` event handler
#   3. Send MIDI messages to the virtual output
#      port via `output.sendMessage(byteArray)`
#   4. Encapsulate received MIDI bytes in UDP
#      datagrams for transmission to the remote
#      peer
#   5. Replay UDP-received MIDI bytes via the
#      virtual output port (so local DAWs see
#      remote MIDI as incoming on the JetMIDI
#      virtual port)
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 269 :: MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital
#              Interface) device I/O libraries
#              (cross-platform MIDI 1.0 spec +
#              USB MIDI Class + sysex message
#              handling)
# Round 1507 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 269
#                                       (262nd axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : Boddlnagg/midir            [R1505 _flow-8-midi]
#             (Patrick Klein; canonical
#              Rust MIDI; pure-Rust)
#   Go      : gomidi/midi                [R1506 _hidi]
#             (Marc Rene Arns; canonical
#              Go MIDI; multi-driver
#              framework)
#   TS/Node : justinlatimer/node-midi    [R1507 THIS FILE]
#             (Justin Latimer; canonical
#              Node MIDI; rtmidi C++
#              wrapper via node-gyp)
#
# justinlatimer/node-midi closes Axis 269 with
# the *rtmidi-wrapper canonical* pattern. The
# three lanes demonstrate the spectrum of
# cross-language MIDI library implementation
# strategies:
#
#   - Rust (midir): pure-Rust; bindgen-generated
#     OS API bindings; no C/C++ dependency
#   - Go (gomidi): multi-driver framework;
#     pure-Go ALSA + cgo-wrapped rtmidi +
#     cgo-wrapped portmidi; consumer chooses
#     backend
#   - Node (node-midi): single-driver C++
#     wrapper; rtmidi via node-gyp; no
#     pure-JS option (jzz uses Web MIDI API
#     which isn't a stdlib in Node)
#
# Each lane's choice reflects language culture:
#   - Rust: prefers pure-language single
#     implementation
#   - Go: prefers multi-driver abstraction
#     with opt-in cgo
#   - Node: prefers native addons via
#     node-gyp for performance-critical I/O
#
# Cross-language interop at the MIDI message
# byte level - all three libraries send +
# receive byte-identical MIDI messages on the
# wire. Sysex compatibility is universal since
# the message format is defined at the byte
# level.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - flow-8-midi (Rust, midir): cross-platform
#     desktop MIDI controller for the Behringer
#     FLOW 8 digital mixer
#   - hidi (Go, gomidi): Linux HID-to-MIDI
#     translation daemon turning USB devices
#     into MIDI controllers
#   - jetmidi (Node, node-midi): firewall-
#     traversing 2-way MIDI over UDP between
#     two networked hosts
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (hardware
# mixer control / HID-to-MIDI translation /
# network MIDI streaming), three implementation
# strategies (pure-Rust / multi-driver-Go /
# C++-wrapper-Node), all converging on the MIDI
# 1.0 spec byte-format.
#
# Axis 269 closes the round 1507 cycle - 262nd
# axis closed total.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Node author/org cohort
# (now spanning 14 distinct individuals/orgs):
#   - Sindre Sorhus (chalk + ~1000 microlibs)
#   - Matt Ranney + Redis Inc. (node-redis)
#   - Brian Carlson (node-postgres)
#   - Andrey Sitnik (PostCSS + browserslist +
#     nanoid)
#   - Lovell Fuller (sharp)
#   - Paul Miller (noble umbrella)
#   - Devon Govett (foliojs umbrella +
#     lightningcss)
#   - Matteo Collina (undici + pino + fastify)
#   - Isaac Z. Schlueter (3 axes: globbing,
#     TAR, INI; the most-axis-closed Node
#     author)
#   - Vitaly Puzrin + nodeca (js-yaml +
#     markdown-it + pako + argparse + sax +
#     linkify-it)
#   - Sergey Belov + svgo team (svg/svgo)
#   - Matt Zabriskie + axios team (axios)
#   - Stuart Knightley (jszip)
#   - Justin Latimer (node-midi, THIS AXIS)
#
# The Node cohort skews heavily toward
# *specialized-format/protocol canonicals*
# (vs Rust's foundational-library bias or Go's
# stdlib-supplemented approach). Latimer's
# node-midi extends this pattern - a niche but
# canonical library for a specialized vertical
# (MIDI I/O) that no other library has
# displaced in 12+ years of Node ecosystem
# evolution.
# ============================================================================

_jetmidi() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-i --ip)'{-i,--ip}'[destination IP address of remote peer (required)]:host:_hosts' \
        '(-p --port)'{-p,--port}'[local UDP port to bind for receiving]:port:' \
        '(-d --destination)'{-d,--destination}'[remote UDP port to send to]:port:' \
        '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose debugging info]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_jetmidi "$@"
